Trusted GAbbI

(Global Amateur Interchange)

Format

April 30, 2002

Version 0.04

By Darryl Wagoner, WA1GON

And

Michael Keane, K1MK

k1mk@alum.mit.edu

© 2002 Trusted QSL and the American Radio Relay League

Discussion:

 

 

1. Physical Specifications:

Character Set:

·        The “character set” shall be ISO/IEC 10646-1:2000 UCS ("Unicode v3.0")

·        Default encoding of characters shall be UTF-8

·        Readers may (optionally) support UTF-16 encoding [TBR]

o       A GAbbI file object that is encoded in UTF-16 must begin with a two octet signature of #xFEFF (Zero Width No‑Break Space; Byte Order Mark)

o       A compliant GAbbI reader must check for the BOM signature. If the BOM signature is encountered indicating that the following file object is UTF-16 encoded and the reader cannot process UTF-16, the reader shall generate a fatal error

Fields:

<Field_Name:Field_Length[:File_Type]>Field_Value

Field_Name — A sequence of one (1) to thirty-two (32) [TBR] characters from the set [A‑Za‑z0-9 ./?_+-=!@#$%^&*] [TBR]. In determining equivalence and uniqueness field names are case insensitive.

Field_Length — Specification of the length of Field_Value in Unicode characters (not bytes or octets and not symbols or graphemes). The specification is a non-negative decimal integer with no leading zeros composed of the characters [0-9].

Field_Type — (Optional) A specification of the type of the field value

Field_Value — A sequence of Field_Length characters that represent the contents of the field.

Separators:

<eoh> — End of header area. <eoh> shall be present in every GAbbI file object. <eoh> shall signal that the start of data (the first field of the first record) commences with the next ‘<’ to be read.

<eor> — End of physical record.

<eof> — End of logical file. <eof> shall be present in every GAbbI file object. Reader must reset its internal state; new GAbbI header may follow (or physical EOF may follow)

As with field names, separator tags are case insensitive.

2. Field Type Definitions:

Type

Designator

Description

Date

D

Date in ISO 8601 format. Extended format i.e., YYYY‑MM‑DD, is preferred but basic format, YYYYMMDD, is permissible but its use is deprecated/ Valid characters that may appear in the value field are [0-9-][1].

Time

T

Time in ISO 8601 format. Extended format i.e., hh:mm:ssZ is preferred, but basic format, hhmmssZ, and basic format with reduced precision, hhmmZ, are also permissible. Should the time zone designator ‘Z’ be omitted, UTC shall be assumed. Legal characters that may appear in the value field are [0-9A-Z:]1.

Character

C

Character string. Valid characters that may appear in the value field are the set of displayable characters (printable characters plus <SP> and <HT>1. [TBR]

Multi-Line

M

Character string. Legal characters that may appear in the value field are displayable characters plus <CR> and <NL>1. An implementation independent end-of-line delimiter (the two character sequence <CR><NL>) shall be employed to signal logical line breaks. [TBR]

Hexadecimal

H

Fixed point (integer) number in base 1610 (hexadecimal) representation.

Legal characters that may appear in the value field are [0-9A-F-]1.

Numeric

N

A general format number. Use of N is deprecated; field types I, B, O, H or F are preferred alternatives.

Integer

I

Fixed point (integer) number in base 1010 (decimal) representation. Legal characters that may appear in the value field are [0-9-]1.

Binary

B

Fixed point (integer) number in base 210 (binary) representation. Written in big endian order, starting with most significant bit. Legal characters that may appear in the value field are [0-1-]1.

Floating Point

F

Floating-point number in base 1010 (decimal) representation. Legal characters that may appear in the value field are [0-9.-]1.

Octal

O

Fixed-point (integer) number in base 810 (octal) representation. Legal characters that may appear in the value field are [0-7-]1.

Base64

6

Base 64 encoded number (binary string). Line length of base64 encoded object shall be limited to 72 characters and lines shall be broken by use of end-of-line character(s). Legal characters that may appear in the value field are [A-Za-z0-9./=]1.

tCONTACT (Trusted Contact) Record:

The tCONTACT record should contains only information that is unique to that contact. Note that most of the fields are required. This is because these fields are expected to be  different for every contact. For efficiency, the information that is common to several contacts is grouped togther and placed into a tSTATION record. The tSTATION record is logically included in the contact record by means of the STATION_GUID field.

N

Y

Frequency. Describes a two-way (non-crossband) contact[5].

Canonical form shall be frequency in MHz with no greater than 100 mHz precision. A decimal point shall be included. There shall be no leading zeros; there shall be no trailing zeroes after the last significant digit. Only digits and decimal point may appear in the field; commas, plus, minus and alphabetic characters shall not appear.

If the precise frequency is unknown use the Frequency listed in Table 1 for the band used.

tSTATION (Trusted Station) Record:

The tSTATION record contains information that is common to a set logical QSL records; each logical record provides a trusted (signed) set information which is needed to confirm a QSO. When a field appears in a tSTATION record it specifies the default value for that field in each logical record which references that tSTATION record via the  STATION_GUID field. When constructing the logical record from the tSTATION and tCONTACT records, the order of precedence shall be that the appearance of a field in the tCONTACT record supercedes any default value for the field that may have been established by the appearance of the same field in the liked tSTATION record.

4. File Definition:

Record Types:

Record

Description

HEADER

This indicates a logical header record. This record shall be placed before the <eoh> tag.

tCONTACT

This record contains the unique information describing a QSO. All tCONTACT records shall follow the <eoh> tag.

tSTATION

This record contains the common information describing a series of QSOs. Typically, this is information describing the sender and his/her station. All tSTATION records shall precede the <eoh> tag.

QSO

This is also the standard logbook format. To maintain backward compatibility, this is the default record type.

 

 

Sample:

/*

Trusted Global Amateur Interchange Format Data for LOTW

*/

 

<category:4>tQSL

 

<Rec_Type:6>Header                 GAbbI header record, all fields are optional

<GAbbI_Version:4>1.00              GAbbI Version

<GAbbI_#_STATION_Recs:1>1          Optional, but shall be correct if present

<GAbbI_#_CONTACT_Recs:1>1          Optional, but shall be correct if present

<GAbbI_Sender:4>K1MK

<GAbbI_Created_By:12>CT2LoTW 1.00  Name and version of log program

<GAbbI_Created_On:20>2001-11-30T00:10:00Z ISO 8601 Date & Time

<GAbbI_Sig_Algorithm:3>RSA         RSA (default), DSA or ECDSA

<eor>                              End of GAbbI header record

<Rec_Type:8>tSTATION

<Call:4>K1MK                       In tSTATION record, this field is “My” call

<State:2>CT                        U.S. State

<Cnty:13>CT,LITCHFIELD             U.S. County

<CQZ:2>05                          CQ Zone

<ITUZ:2>08                         ITU Zone

<GridSquare:6>FN31ko               Maidenhead Grid Square

<Station_GUID:1>1                  Format of UID/GUID is still TBD

<Cert_GUID>0123456789              Format of Certificate # is still TBD

<eor>                                                                        End of tSTATION record

<eoh>                              End of header area

<Rec_Type:8>tCONTACT

<Call:5>CN8WW                      In tCONTACT record this field is “His” call

<Band:4>160M

<Freq:6>1.8271                     MHz

<QSO_Date:8>2001-11-27             YYYY-MM-DD

<QSO_Time:4>00:00:15Z              HH:MM:[SS]Z (UTC)

<Mode:2>CW                         Mode

<RST_Sent:3>599                    RST

<Station_GUID:1>1                  Format of UID/GUID still TBD

<LoTW_Sign:172>ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcd

efghijklmnopqratuvwxyz0123456789./ABCDEFGHIJK

LMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqratuvwxyz0123

456789./ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijk

lmnop==                                                                   Signature w/1024-bit RSA key

<eor>                                                                        End of tCONTACT record

<eof>                              End of a logical file object

Table 4 – Station Types

Station Type

Description

LAND

A land station is located on land whether fixed or mobile.

MARITIME

A maritime station located on board a ship or boat on the water, whiter the vessel is at anchor or underway, within sovereign territorial waters or on the high seas.

AERONAUTICAL

An aeronautical station is located aboard an aircraft and is operated while the aircraft is airborne.

[1] Illegal characters encountered while scanning a field are to be ignored. The field length shall be interpreted as the number of valid characters to be read. If while scanning a field, the reader encounters an illegal character other than an end-of-line character (<CR> or <NL>), the reader shall issue a warning. If a start of field delimiter ‘<’ is encountered before the expected end of field, the reader shall reject the field being read and issue a warning.

Note that GAbbI is only very weakly armored against line folding and provides no protection against gratuitous character re-mapping that can be introduced by the transport layer, especially e-mail. A prudent precaution would be to encode a GAbbI object using base64 prior to transport by e-mail. This encoding would be mandatory if UTF-8 characters beyond 7-bit ASCII characet set are to be exchanged.  

[2] A compliant GAbbI reader must support RSA signatures. Readers may support DSA and ECDSA signatures. If a reader is presented with data signed using a public key algorithm that the reader does not support, the reader shall generate a fatal error.

[3] Field is required to appear in the logical contact record. Physically this field may appear either in the station record or the contact record. When constructing the logical contact record from the tSTATION and tCONTACT records, there is an order of precedence that the appearance of any field in the tCONTACT record shall supercede any default value for the field that might have been set by an occurrence of the same field in the linked tSTATION record.

[4] To indicate a cross-band contact the pair of fields: BAND_RX and BAND_TX shall be used. If the BAND field appears in a record then neither BAND_RX nor BAND_TX may appear. If either the BAND_RX or BAND_TX field appears, then both fields must appear.

[5] To indicate a split-frequency (or cross-band) contact the pair of fields: FREQ_RX and FREQ_TX shall be used. If the FREQ field appears in a record then neither FREQ_RX nor FREQ_TX may appear. If either the FREQ_RX or FREQ_TX field appears, then both fields must appear.

[6] To indicate a cross-mode contact the pair of fields: MODE_RX and MODE_TX shall be used. If the MODE field appears in a record then neither MODE_RX nor MODE_TX may appear. If either the MODE_RX or MODE_TX field appears, then both fields must appear.

[7] If needed for an explicit declaration, the non-callsign value of NONE for REPEATER shall be permitted.

[8] Use of a SAT_MODE equal to EME shall be used to indicate an Earth-Moon-Earth (moonbounce) contact. The corresponding SAT_NAME shall be MOON.
